MYCOBACTERIUM ULCERANS - AUSTRALIA (VICTORIA)
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Thu 15 Jul 2004
From: Paul Johnson <Paul.Johnson@austin.org.au>

A new endemic cluster of _Mycobacterium ulcerans_ infection has appeared
near Melbourne, Australia. The town of Point Lonsdale is a coastal resort,
an approximately one hour drive south of central Melbourne on the Bellarine
Peninsula. 6 infections in visitors or residents of Point Lonsdale have
been diagnosed in the last 2 months [June and July 2004].
Although _M. ulcerans_ has been present on the Bellarine peninsula for the
last 6 years, including some cases from Point Lonsdale, the close temporal
and geographical clustering of these recent cases is a cause for concern. A
similar cluster occurred at a nearby town, St. Leonards, in 2001. A team of
health department officials and researchers are about to visit the area in
an attempt to identify a point source. However, as the incubation period
for _M. ulcerans_ has a median of around 13 weeks, transmission probably
occurred in late summer or autumn 2004. It is now winter in southeastern
Australia, with typical daytime temperatures of 12-14 degrees Celsius
[53-57 degrees Fahrenheit]. _Mycobacterium ulcerans_ infection (also known
as Buruli ulcer) is most prevalent in rural west and sub-Saharan Africa,
and, it is not known why this tropical disease also occurs in temperate
southeastern Australia.
The precise mode of transmission is also unknown, but the endemic areas in
Victoria are, typically, low-lying coastal regions with tidal and/or swampy
features, lakes, or slow flowing rivers. Possible modes of transmission
include, mosquitoes, sand flies, tabanids (March flies), aerosol contact,
or direct contact with contaminated soil or vegetation.
At least 2 other cases of _M. ulcerans_ infection not linked to Point
Lonsdale have been reported to the Victorian Department of Human Services
during 2004. People who live on, or visit, Point Lonsdale, or other known
endemic areas in the state of Victoria -- including east Gippsland, the
Gippsland lakes, Phillip Island, the Mornington peninsula, and the
Bellarine peninsula -- should report unusual slowly progressive skin
lesions to their doctors and ask that the diagnosis of _M. ulcerans_
infection be considered. Treatment is relatively straightforward when the
diagnosis is made early. [The treatment, as discussed below, is primarily
surgical. - Mod.LL]
--
Prof. Paul Johnson
Deputy Director, Infectious Diseases
Austin Health
Melbourne, Australia
<paul.johnson@austin.org.au>
