[2]
Date: Thu 14 Jul 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Herald Sun [edited]
<http://www.heraldsun.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,5478,10139000%
255E1702,00.html>

Rare ulcer outbreak in coastal town
---------------------------------
Victorian health authorities are investigating a suspected outbreak of a
rare ulcer condition in a coastal holiday town.
6 people -- residents of Point Lonsdale on Victoria's Bellarine Peninsula,
and visitors to holiday homes in the area -- have been diagnosed with a
condition known as the Bairnsdale ulcer, the state's chief health officer,
Robert Hall, said today, Thu 15 Jul 2004.
The condition, also known as _Mycobacterium ulcerans_, is a rare infection
that causes chronic, progressive skin ulcer on exposed parts of the body,
such as the arms or legs, Dr. Hall said.
"It can begin as a painless, or itchy, lesion that breaks down to form an
ulcer."
Dr. Hall advised anyone who had a skin sore, lump, or ulcer that was not
healing to contact a doctor for testing.
The Bairnsdale ulcer, which is not thought to be contagious, gets its name
from the local area in which an outbreak among farmers was documented in
1948. Between 5 and 20 cases are reported in Australia each year. The
bacteria are found naturally in the environment, but the way it infects
humans is unknown.
